<subsection xml:id="subsec-operations-with-fractions" >
    <title>Operation with fractions</title>
    
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-addition-and-subtraction-of-fractions">
        <title>Aaddition and subtraction of two or three unlike and mixed fractions.</title>

        <definition xml:id="def-mixed-numbers">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In everyday life, you often come across situations 
                    where we need to add or subtract parts of a whole—like pieces of 
                    cake, distances, or time. These parts are represented as fractions. 
                    Sometimes, we deal with mixed numbers, which are whole numbers combined 
                    with fractions, like <m>2 \frac{1}{2}</m> In this lesson, you’ll learn how to add 
                    and subtract mixed numbers with unlike denominators.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Remember:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="i. ">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <term>Mixed fractions</term>   are numbers like <m>3 \frac{2}{5}</m> which means <m>3</m> wholes and <m>\frac{2}{5}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <term>Unlike fractions </term> are fractions with different denominators, such as 
                                <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> and <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Adding mixed fractions}</m>
        </p>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Juma's family was expecting visitors that evening. In preparation, Juma's mother bought <m>1 \frac{1}{2}</m> kg of meat.
                    Later, his father bought an additional <m>2 \frac{1}{4}</m> kg of meat to ensure there was enough for everyone. How much meat did they have altogether?
                </p>
                <p>
                    Share your work with other learners in the class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            To add two mixed fractions, we first add the whole nummbers parts, then Add the 
            fraction part and finally add the whole number and the fraction.
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Work out: <m>7 \frac{2}{5}+3 \frac{1}{4}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The following steps are followed:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Step 1:}</m> Add the whole numbers: <m>7+3=10</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Step 2:}</m> Add the fractions: <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{2}{5}+\frac{1}{4}=\amp \frac{8+5}{20} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{8}{20}+ \frac{5}{20} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{13}{20} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Step 3:}</m> Add the new whole number to new fraction:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 10+\frac{13}{20}=\amp 10 \frac{13}{20} </mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>
            <m>\text{Subtracting mixed fractions}</m>
        </p>
        <activity>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    <alert>Work in groups</alert>
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Make the fraction cards like the one shown below.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    
                    <image source="mixed-fractions-number-card.png">
                        <shortdescription>Number cards containing operation between twp mixed numbers</shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Pick any fraction card and subtract the fractions.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        
                       Share your work with other learners in your class.
                        
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            
        </activity>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Work out: <m>12 \frac{2}{3}- 7 \frac{3}{5}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The following steps are followed:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Step 1:}</m> Subtract the whole numbers: <m>12-7=5</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Step 2:}</m> Subtract the fractions: <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{2}{3}-\frac{3}{5}=\amp \frac{10-9}{15} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{10}{15}- \frac{9}{15} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{15} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Step 3:}</m> Add the new whole number to new fraction:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 5+\frac{1}{15}=\amp 5 \frac{1}{15} </mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    
        <activity>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Work in pairs}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Get into pairs. Each group receives two sets of mixed 
                            numbers written on cards. Your task is to:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Add the mixed numbers in the first set.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Subtract the mixed numbers in the second set.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your steps and answers with the class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a) ">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Always start by adding/subtracting whole numbers first.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Convert unlike fractions to like fractions
                        by finding the LCM of the denominators.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Simplify your answer when possible.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        You may also convert mixed numbers to improper 
                        fractions for easier calculation in some cases.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Add the following:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a. "> 
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2 \frac{2}{5}+ 1 \frac{2}{3}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>7 \frac{3}{4}+ 12 \frac{2}{7}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a. ">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Add the whole numbers: <m>2+1=3</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Add the fractions: 
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\frac{2}{5} + \frac{2}{3} =\amp \frac{6+10}{15} </mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp  \frac{6}{15} + \frac{10}{15}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{16}{15} </mrow>
                                </md>
                                Now add to the whole number:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>3+ \frac{16}{15}= \amp 3 + 1 \frac{1}{15} </mrow>
                                    <mrow>= \amp 4 \frac{1}{15} </mrow>
                                </md>
            
            
            
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Add the whole numbers: <m>7+12=19</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Add the fractions: 
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\frac{3}{4} + \frac{2}{7} =\amp \frac{21+8}{28} </mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp  \frac{21}{28} + \frac{8}{21}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{29}{28} </mrow>
                                </md>
                                Now add to the whole number:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>19+ \frac{29}{28}= \amp 19 + 1 \frac{1}{28} </mrow>
                                    <mrow>= \amp 20 \frac{1}{28} </mrow>
                                </md>
            
            
            
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Work out the following:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a. ">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2 \frac{4}{5} - 1 \frac{2}{3}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>1 \frac{1}{2}+ 2 \frac{1}{4} + 1 \frac{2}{3}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a. "> 
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Subtract the whole numbers: <m>2-1=1</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Subtract the fractions: 
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\frac{4}{5} - \frac{2}{3} =\amp \frac{12-10}{15} </mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp  \frac{12}{15} - \frac{10}{15}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{2}{15} </mrow>
                                </md>
                                Now add to the new whole number:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>1+ \frac{2}{15}= \amp 1\frac{1}{15} </mrow>
                                    
                                </md>
            
            
            
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               Add the whole numbers: <m>1+2+1=4</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Add the fractions: 
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{4}+ \frac{2}{3} =\amp \frac{6+3+8}{12} </mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp  \frac{6}{12} + \frac{3}{12}+\frac{8}{12}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{17}{12} </mrow>
                                </md>
                                Now add to the whole number:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>4+ \frac{17}{12}= \amp 4 + 1 \frac{5}{12} </mrow>
                                    <mrow>= \amp 5 \frac{5}{12} </mrow>
                                </md>



                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve: <m>3 \frac{1}{4} -1 \frac{2}{3}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Step 2}</m>: Convert both to improper fractions:
                    <m>3 \frac{1}{4}= \frac{13}{4}</m>, <m>\ \frac{2}{3}=\frac{5}{3}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Step 1}</m>: Find LCM of <m>4</m> and <m>3</m> → LCM <m>=12</m>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{13}{4}=\amp \frac{39}{12} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \frac{5}{3}=\amp \frac{20}{12} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Step 3}</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{39}{12}-\frac{20}{12} =\amp  \frac{19}{12}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 1 \frac{7}{12} </mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-addition-and-subtraction-of-fractions-2">
        <title>Solving problems involving addition or subtraction of fractions.</title>

        <definition xml:id="def-problems">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In real-life situations, we often need to add 
                    or subtract fractions to solve problems. Whether it's sharing food, measuring ingredients, or calculating distances, understanding 
                    how to work with fractions is essential.
                </p>
                <p>
                    When solving such problems:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="i. ">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Read the question carefully.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Identify the fractions involved.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Make sure the fractions have the same denominator before adding or subtracting.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Simplify your answer if possible.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
                </p>
                
                <p>
                    <term>What you need:</term>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Printed word problem cards (about <m>8-10</m> different problems)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Plain A4 sheets or exercise books
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Timer or stopwatch
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Chalkboard or whiteboard
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Sample Problem Cards:
                </p>
                <image source="/cards.png" >
                    <shortdescription>cards</shortdescription>
                </image>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                

                                <m>\textbf{Form Groups:}</m> Divide the class into small groups of <m>3-5</m> students.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\textbf{Set the Relay:}</m> Place the word problem cards 
                                at the front of the class (or station them in different corners of the room).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\textbf{Relay Rules:}</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            One member from each group runs to pick a card.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            They bring the card back and the whole group works together to solve it.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            Once they solve it, they write the answer on their sheet.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            Then, a different member runs to pick the next card.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\textbf{Time Limit:}</m> Set a time limit 
                                (e.g., <m>15</m> minutes). The group that correctly solves the most problems within the time wins!
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\textbf{Class Review:}</m> After the activity, go over each question as a class 
                                and discuss the different methods used.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

            </statement>
        </activity>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Ama used <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>kg of flour to bake bread in the morning and <m>\frac{3}{8}</m> kg in the 
                    afternoon. How much flour did she use in total?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{1}{4}+ \frac{3}{8}=\amp \frac{2+3}{8} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{2}{8}+ \frac{3}{8} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{5}{8} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Ama used <m>{\color{blue} \frac{5}{8} }</m> kg of flour in total.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Nana cycled  <m>2 \frac{1}{2}</m> km in the morning and <m>3 \frac{2}{3}</m>km in the evening.
                     What is the total distance he cycled in a day?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Add the whole numbers: <m>2+3=5</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Add the fractions: 
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{1}{2}+ \frac{2}{3}=\amp \frac{3+4}{6} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{3}{6} + \frac{4}{6} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{7}{6} </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 1 \frac{1}{6} </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Add to the whole number: 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>5+ 1 \frac{1}{6}= \amp 6 \frac{1}{6} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Yaw cycled <m>{\color{blue} 6 \frac{1}{6} }</m> km in total.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A container had <m>4 \frac{3}{5}</m>
                    litres of water. After using <m>2 \frac{2}{3}</m> litres, how much water is left?
                </p>

            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The amount of water left is given by; 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>4 \frac{3}{5}- 2 \frac{2}{3}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Subtract the whole numbers: <m>4-2=2</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Subtract the fractions: 
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{3}{5}- \frac{2}{3}=\amp \frac{9-10}{15} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{9}{15} - \frac{10}{15} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp -\frac{1}{15} </mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                    Add to the whole number: 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2+(- \frac{1}{15})= \amp  \frac{30-1}{15} </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp \frac{30}{15}- \frac{1}{15} </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp \frac{29}{15} </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 1 \frac{14}{15} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>{\color{blue} 1 \frac{14}{15}}</m> litres of water is left.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Kojo studied for  <m>1 \frac{3}{4}</m> hours on Monday and <m>2 \frac{1}{3}</m> hours on Tuesday. 
                    How much more time did he study on Tuesday than on Monday?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    How much more days implies that you subtract the hours read 
                    on Monday from Tuesday reading time. as shown;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>2 \frac{1}{3}= 1 \frac{3}{4}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Convert to improper fractions:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>1 \frac{3}{4}= \amp  \frac{7}{4} </mrow>
                        <mrow>2 \frac{1}{3}= \amp \frac{7}{3} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Find LCM of <m>4</m> and <m>3</m> → LCM <m>= 12</m>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{7}{4}=\amp \frac{21}{12} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \frac{7}{3}=\amp \frac{28}{12} </mrow>
                       
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Subtract
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{28}{12} -\frac{21}{12}=\amp \frac{7}{12} </mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Kojo studied <m>{\color{blue} \frac{7}{12}}</m>hours more on Tuesday than on Monday.
                    
                </p>
            </solution>

        </example>
    </subsubsection>

